item.label: Dura
item.name: Dura
item.description: The dura mater is the outermost and thickest collagenous layer of the three layers of meninges. Within the skull its 'outer' layer adheres tightly to the inside of the skull, constituting the periosteum. An 'inner' meningeal layer separates out as reflections between parts of the cerebral hemisphere, i.e. cerebral falx or between the cerebral hemispheres and posterior fossa, i.e. tentorium cerebelli. In the spinal dura mater there is a single layer separated from the vertebral periosteum by the epidural space.

item.label: Meningeal arteries
item.name: Meningeal Arteries
item.description: There are three paired meningeal arteries:  anterior, middle and posterior.  The middle meningeal artery is the largest and most clinically significant.  These vessels travel in the periosteal layer of the dura and supply both the dura and the calvarium.

item.label: Superior sagittal sinus
item.name: Superior Sagittal Sinus
item.description: The superior sagittal sinus of the dural venous sinus system is located in the superior midline of the cerebral dura and thus, in the superior, attached edge of the cerebral falx. It receives venous blood from cerebral, diploic and emissary veins and joins the remainder of the sinus system at the confluence in the sinuses near the internal occipital protuberance.

item.label: Cerebral veins, Superficial
item.name: Cerebral Vein
item.description: Cerebral veins are described as superficial or deep, depending on whether they drain the superficial or deep aspects of the brain.  In general, the superficial veins lie on the surface of the cerebral hemispheres, where most empty into the superior sagittal sinus.

item.label: Arachnoid membrane
item.name: Arachnoid membrane
item.description: The arachnoid is one of three meningeal layers associated with the brain and spinal cord. It is located between the dura mater and pia mater. The space between the arachnoid and pia is filled with cerebrospinal fluid and contains a trabecular network connecting the arachnoid with the pia.

item.label: Arachnoid villi
item.name: Arachnoid villi
item.description: Arachnoid villi are AKA arachnoid granulations. They are small evaginations of the arachnoid membrane that protrude through the dura mater and into the lumen of a dural venous sinus, such as the superior sagittal sinus. They are the site of reabsorption of cerebrospinal fluid from the subarachnoid space back into the venous system.
